<DOC><DOCNO> AP880713-0272 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-07-13-88 1021EDT</FILEID><FIRST>u f PM-WallStreet10am     07-13 0301</FIRST><SECOND>PM-Wall Street 10am,0317</SECOND><DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   The stock market edged upward today in adrifting summer session.   The Dow Jones average of 30 industrials rose 2.84 to 2,095.48 inthe first half hour of trading.   Gainers outnumbered losers by about 5 to 4 in the early tally ofNew York Stock Exchange-listed issues, with 497 up, 381 down and503 unchanged.   Volume on the Big Board came to 30.29 million shares as of 10a.m. on Wall Street.   Close to half of that activity came on dividend-related tradingin a single issue, Pacific Enterprises, which was up [ at 47.   Otherwise, analysts said many market participants were holdingback awaiting Friday's report from the Commerce Department on thenation's international trade balance for May.   Some observers worry that the recent run of favorable trade newsmight have about run its course, or that continued strength inexports might provide a fresh signal of potential credit-tighteningby the Federal Reserve.   Alan Greenspan, the Fed's chairman, told a congressionalcommittee today that the Fed took several steps to restrain theeconomy in recent months with the aim of keeping inflation in check.   Among actively traded blue chips, Exxon rose [ to 44|; GeneralElectric gained [ to 42]; American Telephone andamp; Telegraph dropped [to 26[, and International Business Machines was down [ at 125[.   The NYSE's composite index of all its listed common stocks added.15 to 151.77. At the American Stock Exchange, the market valueindex was down .07 at 307.24.   On Tuesday the Dow Jones industrial average fell 18.67 to2,092.64.   Declining issues outnumbered advancing ones about 7 to 3 on theNYSE, with 442 issues up, 1,039 down and 481 unchanged. Big Boardvolume totaled 161.65 million shares, up from 123.30 million in theprevious session.</TEXT></DOC>